{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01EvTNSb1zU2ZEyDno4uwiSd","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The app-data index doesn't exist yet. I need to create it. Let me check more about what exists.\n\nActually, looking at the goal again:\n- \"Ensure shards for index 'app-data' relocate onto the new nodes\"\n\nThis suggests I need to create the app-data index (or it should exist already - let me look more carefully). The verification says \"app-data shards are present on nodes outside the original 3\", so I need to:\n\n1. Create the app-data index (if it doesn't exist)\n2. Make sure its shards end up on the new nodes\n\nThe approach:\n1. Update es-config ConfigMap to add `node.attr.zone: original` to existing nodes\n2. Create a new ConfigMap for the new nodes with `node.attr.zone: new`\n3. Spin up a new StatefulSet with 2 replicas that join the cluster\n4. Create the app-data index with shard allocation rules targeting the new zone\n\nBut I'm realizing that modifying the existing ConfigMap and restarting those pods could cause cluster disruption. I should look for a way to set node attributes without rolling restarts.\n\nActually, I can just add the new nodes with their own zone attribute and configure the app-data index to route shards only to those new nodes. For the existing nodes, I could update their ConfigMap to add `node.attr.zone: original`, though that would require a rolling restart. Let me think about whether that's necessary for the verification requirement.\n\nThe new nodes need to join the cluster with the same cluster name, TLS certificates, and discovery service, plus they need to be included in the initial master nodes configuration. them to be data-only nodes without master eligibility, which is better for scaling. I'm planning to create a separate ConfigMap for these new nodes with the same cluster settings but explicitly setting them as data-only, then create a new StatefulSet that uses this config and the same image and secrets as the existing cluster.\n\nNow I need to think through the service discovery piece—the new pods need to be discoverable by the existing nodes. The headless service `es-headless` already handles transport discovery on port 9300, so if I give the new StatefulSet pods the same `app: elasticsearch` label, they'll automatically be included in that service's DNS. However, I need to decide whether to use the same headless service or create a separate one for the new data nodes.\n\nActually, I can reuse `es-headless` by giving the new pods the matching label. When Elasticsearch resolves `discovery.seed_hosts: es-headless`, it'll get all pod IPs including the new ones, allowing them to join the cluster. Let me plan out the configuration for the new data node setup.\n\nI'm creating a ConfigMap with Elasticsearch settings that designates these as data-only nodes with a different zone attribute, then setting up a StatefulSet with 2 replicas that uses the same headless service and shares the security configuration. Once the new nodes join the cluster, I can create the app-data index.\n\nNow I'm clarifying what \"different allocation attribute\" means—whether the original nodes need their own attribute value that differs from the new nodes, or if the new nodes simply have an attribute the originals lack. Either way, I need to ensure the allocation attributes are set up so I can route the index to prefer the new nodes.\n\nI'm thinking through whether to update the existing ConfigMap to add `node.attr.zone: original` and then perform a rolling restart of the existing pods. Since the cluster is healthy with replicas, this should maintain stability, though the readiness probe delay will make the process slower.\n\nI also need to check if the `app-data` index exists yet—looking at the current indices, there's only `test-index`, so I'll need to create it. My approach is to update the config for original nodes, spin up the new data nodes with their own config, create the app-data index with routing constraints to the new zone, and then restart the existing pods to pick up their zone attribute. Now I'm considering how to verify this setup is working correctly. Rolling restart should be manageable since the cluster maintains quorum with 3 nodes. I'm thinking through the safest sequence: spin up the new data nodes first to give the cluster time to stabilize, then create the app-data index with routing configured for the new zone, and finally do a rolling restart of the existing nodes to pick up the zone attribute.\n\nOne thing I need to verify is whether the new pods with the `app: elasticsearch` label will also get exposed through the `es-http` service—if that service uses the same selector, I might need to be careful about how traffic gets routed.\n\nWriting elasticsearch.yml config... Writing config file...\n\nI'm thinking through whether I need a separate headless service for the new StatefulSet or if I can reuse the existing one—multiple StatefulSets can point to the same headless service as long as it exists. I need to make sure the new pods get the `app: elasticsearch` label so they're included in the `es-headless` service endpoints, and I should set the new StatefulSet's `serviceName` to `es-headless` as well so they get the correct DNS subdomain. This way all nodes can discover each other through the same headless service for cluster formation.\n\nSince the existing StatefulSet uses `emptyDir` for storage, I'll do the same for the new one. Now I'm ready to implement the plan: update the config with zone attributes, create the new StatefulSet with 2 replicas, wait for them to be ready, then create the index with proper routing and handle the rolling restart of the original pods.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":650,"cache_read_input_tokens":33666,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens